Scientists have found an animal that can live 500 years
An international group of biologists has concluded that the longest-living vertebrate animal is the Greenlandic polar shark, which can live for about 500 years, RT reports.
Scientists conducted a radiocarbon analysis of the eye crystals of 28 Greenland sharks.
The largest shark, whose length exceeds five meters, can be from 272 to 512 years.
Biologists believe that an important role in shark longevity is played by low metabolism, which leads to slow development.
Females of Greenland sharks reach sexual maturity only by the age of 150.
Previously, it was believed that longer than all vertebrate animals live the "neighbor" shark - the Greenlandic whale.
The oldest known individual, the scientist, was just over 210 years old.
