The Spiritual Authority of Muslims (DUM) of Tatarstan refuses to use the Russian language in mosques.
Yesterday, the plenum of DUM required its imams to preach Friday only in Tatar to force young Tatars to "learn their native language".
The government says it does not "under any circumstances violate" the rights of Muslims of other nationalities.
In some Kazan mosques it is said that the Tatar language is not understood by up to 60% of the parishioners, including foreign students, migrants and the Tatars themselves.
The Imams fear that their sermons in Tatar “will not reach the entire audience.”
Yesterday, the plenum of the Duma of Tatarstan unanimously decided to hold Friday sermons in the mosques of the Republic only in Tatar language.
As Tatarstan mufti Camille Samigullin said, it should be an incentive for young Tatars “to learn their native language”.
“For those who will say ‘it’s hard,’ in every big mosque we intend to organize lessons in the Tatar language absolutely free of charge,” Mr. Samigullin promised.
He added that “the decision has already come into force” and today in all mosques the sermons “should already be in the Tatar language.”
He recalled that the DUM of Tatarstan publishes the magazine "Shura" with typical sermons in the Tatar language.
Imam, who does not speak well enough in Tatar, "can be thoroughly prepared for it".
The DUM of Tatarstan brings together more than a thousand revenues in all the municipalities of the republic.
According to Mufti, Friday sermons are held exclusively in the Tatar language.
At the same time, Russian language was used in a number of mosques in Kazan.
In particular, as Mufti pointed out, this was practiced in the Burnaev Mosque, Zakabanna and Eniler.
However, Mr. Mukhametshin stressed, the leadership is tasked with ensuring that all students possess both state languages of the republic, regardless of nationality.
“There can be no mention of any harm to a non-Muslim,” Mr. Muhammedshin said, explaining that the sermon itself “is not a mandatory, basic part of the prayer.”
At the same time, the prayer itself will still be read in Arabic, lectures and lessons in Russian will be kept in the mosques.
At the same time, Rafik Muhametshin said "I" that there was no serious threat of expelling the Tatar language from the mosques.
In addition to Russian and Tatar, other languages, such as Uzbek or Tajik, are not used in the sermons in the republic.
The decision of the DUM was actively supported by the Executive Committee of the World Congress of Tatars (WCC).
The head of the executive committee of the VCT, Rinat Zakirov, said "I": "Smeets are an important part of our national life."
It would be sad if the Tatar language had gone out of this sphere.
He noted that preaching only in the Tatar language "is the wish of the imams themselves", but in the executive branch of the ICC "it is considered right".
The interrogated "I" imams, who preached in Russian, are ready to fulfill the decision of the DUM, but believe that the parishioners will have difficulty with understanding the clergy.
Both the Tatars and the Russians go to the mosque.
Many do not understand the language.
They will, of course, be sad.
“It will have to be rebuilt,” says the imams of the Burnaev Mosque Farhat Mavletdinov.
According to him, preaching in Russian is closer even to many Tatars, because "Russian in schools, and in kindergartens, on the radio - everywhere originally".
However, he believes that the mosque will be able to continue lessons and lectures in Russian, which are held on other days.
We trust in God.
Allah will show you the way out of this situation," he concluded.
But about 60% of us do not know the Tatar language.
These are Uzbeks, Tajiks, and Azerbaijanis.
There are a lot of foreign students coming to us: Africans, Arabs.
“That’s why we switched to Russian for four years,” says the imam.
He believes that in the Tatar language, the sermons will “reach to a narrower circle and will not reach the entire audience.”
But we will be subject to the decision of the plenum.
The end of the sermon will be different.
But time will show.
"For me, for example, it will only be easier, because the Tatar language is my native language," said Gabdulla Galliullin.
