The Prosecutor’s Office of Moscow has approved an indictment on the investigated criminal case of theft of budget funds allocated for the needs of the FSIN of Russia.
Former head of the prison department Alexander Reimer and his deputy, who caused more than 2.7 billion rubles of damage to FSIN, will be brought before the court.
The capital prosecutor’s office has sent a criminal case against the former director of FSIN of Russia Alexander Reymer, his former deputy Nikolai Krivolapova, as well as the director of the FGUP “Information and Technical Security and Liaison Center” to the Zamoskvoretsky district court.
Depending on the role and degree of participation in the commission of crimes, they are accused of GSU SKR in Moscow pursuant to Article 3 of Article 285 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (abuse of official powers, which has had serious consequences).The number of the service is a serious consequence, Article 4 of Article 159 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (fraud).
In addition, Kryvolapov is charged under Article 1 of Article 222 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (illegal acquisition and storage of ammunition).
According to the CRC, in 2010-2012, these persons were fraudulently kidnapped from the state treasury by the budget funds allocated to the FSIN to provide the department with electronic monitoring systems of controlled persons, so-called electronic bracelets.
For the theft of budget money, the group members developed a scheme according to which the company under its control FGUP CITOS, with which the relevant public contracts were concluded, produced technical means of control and supervision in this field, including "electronic bracelets", and relays.
Despite the fact that FGUP CITOS did not have production equipment, buildings, facilities for the placement of production capacities, allowing to create the final cycle of production of "electronic bracelets", between it and the FSIN of Russia were concluded five state contracts for a sum of 3 more.
As a result of this scheme, the accounts of the Samar branch of FGUP amounted to more than 2 billion rubles, of which 1.2 billion rubles were stolen.
According to the investigation, more than 140 million rubles of cash received personally by Mr. Reimer in his office from one of the accomplices, the criminal case in respect of which is allocated in separate proceedings.
Nikolai Krivolapov, who participated in the machinations, was found of unknown origin of the cartridge for the reward gun, which allowed him to submit an additional charge.
In the present case, which amounted to 133 volumes, FSIN has filed a claim for damages of 2.7 billion rubles against the accused.
