The Russian Copper Company (RMK) is ready to take on social responsibility and pay more attention to the environmental aspects of its business.
This is confirmed, for example, by the fact that the RMK has undertaken to modernize one of the country’s oldest and environmentally “dirty” enterprises – the Karabakh Honeycomb.
The Carabash Honey Smelting Plant was founded by an English stock company headed by Leslie Urkwart in 1910.
In Soviet times it was a significant industrial enterprise for the economy of the country, and it actually provided the life of the whole city.
However, in the 1990s due to financial problems, production was halted, which led to serious social problems in Karabakh.
In 1998, it was decided to resume work of the Karabakh Honeycomb.
It was also necessary to solve one of the main problems of the Karabakh plant - environmental.
By the early 2000s, Karabach was already sadly known as an environmental disaster zone.
The situation at Karabashmedi began to change in 2004, after the enterprise was transferred to the management of the Russian copper company.
The company began to carry out the modernization of production, which began to gradually reduce the environmental burden on the environment.
This was recently noted by the governor of the Chelyabinsk region, Boris Dubrovsky, who visited Karabakh in early July.
The head of the Southern Ural called the huge changes that have occurred with the enterprise since "Karabashmed" moved into the group of RMK.
The main event for the modernization of Karabashmedi in recent years has been the construction of a new sulfuric acid workshop, which allows to capture up to 99.9% of metallurgical gases.
According to the president of the Russian copper company Vsevolod Levin, the volume of investments in this project amounted to about 7 billion rubles.
The next stage of the modernization of ZAO "Karabashmed" is the reconstruction of the conversion plant.
The replacement of three converters, vacuum cleaners and gas pipelines is planned for the end of 2017.
The cost of the project is 2.5 billion rubles.
In addition, at the end of 2016 it is planned to launch a new factory for the treatment of industrial waste at the cost of 1 billion rubles.
In turn, the amounts of taxes deducted into the city budget of Karabas will also increase.
For the entire duration of the implementation of the Tominsky GOK project - from the beginning of construction to the commissioning of the second row - the federal fine will receive 8.9 billion rubles.
And after the introduction of GOK into operation, the income of taxes in the budgets of all levels can amount to 80.9 billion rubles.
For the year of production work in the Varna district, the budgets of different levels are listed 346,3 million rubles.
And that's for the first year.
"The longer the enterprise works successfully, the amount of deductions may be more," - added Valery Ulanovsky.
The RMK clarified that in 2015 the tax deductions from the Mikheev GOK were approximated to 1 billion rubles.
However, the participation of RMK enterprises in the life and development of the territories of their presence is not limited to tax deductions.
RMC enterprises help to repair and maintain schools, kindergartens, sports facilities, to build cultural and entertainment facilities, to improve the territory.
In 2016, one of the largest social projects of the Russian copper company in Karabakh was a major repair, and in fact - the almost complete renovation of the kindergarten N9 for 95 pupils.
The building, built in 1960, was in a state of emergency.
Also on the territory of "RMK Arena" there will be a landscape park with an artificial pond, underground and underground parking spaces for 600 cars, cafes and sports shops.
"RMK Arena" will allow to conduct spectacular professional sporting events of international level.
But the main task of this project is to make physical education and sports in comfortable conditions accessible to the inhabitants of Chelyabinsk, primarily for children.
