WSJ: The U.S. is considering imposing sanctions against Russia for hacking the servers of Democrats.
U.S. officials are considering the imposition of new sanctions against Russia in response to the hacking of the Democratic Party’s servers, the Wall Street Journal writes, citing sources.
It is reported that in order to impose sanctions, the administration of US President Barack Obama will have to formally accuse of attacking Russian servers or Russian-backed hackers.
According to the sources, the FBI and other U.S. intelligence agencies are almost certain of Russia’s involvement in the cyber attack.
WSJ notes that the U.S. usually prefers not to name those who carry out hacking attacks.
The exception is a 2014 hack of the Sony Entertainment Pictures database, for which responsibility was officially assigned to the DPRK.
Last year, however, Obama issued a decree that simplifies the procedure for imposing sanctions on those who carry out or promote cyberattacks.
It was originally aimed at China, but could also be used against other countries.
The decision-making process on sanctions can be lengthy, writes the publication.
Even if officials came to the conclusion that the hackers acted with the support of Russia, before deciding to disclose the information they will have to weigh the possible consequences.
They have to determine whether the incident is so serious that it exacerbates the tensions in the bilateral relationship.
Earlier it was reported that the Obama administration allows the possibility of sanctions against the state, whose hackers hacked the servers of the National Committee of the Democratic Party.
WikiLeaks has published an e-mail from the National Committee of Democrats.
The media reported that hackers working with the Russian authorities could be involved in the hack.
