"Generation protests" in Ethiopia, long-time U.S. ally
Angry protests in Ethiopia
Demonstrators demanding political change in Ethiopia have been confronted with a fierce confrontation by the government.
Eyewitnesses say dozens of protesters were fatally wounded during clashes with police.
Is Ethiopia really on the brink of fragmentation?
Over the past decade, it has been one of Africa’s most stable countries, a strong ally of the West with a rapidly developing economy.
But in recent months, anti-government protests have shaken the country, spreading to an increasing number of its territories.
In the past week alone, thousands of people have taken to the streets demanding radical political changes.
According to human rights defenders, the government’s reaction was brutal.
Eyewitnesses claimed that police officers shot dozens of unarmed demonstrators.
Video footage from the protest sites, supposedly shot late last year or early this year, shows how security officers beat young people with sticks when they put their hands against the wall.
The United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights is now calling for a thorough investigation.
“It has always been difficult to keep this country from falling apart, and it will continue to be even more difficult,” said Rashid Abdi, head of the African Horn project at the international research crisis group.
Ethiopia is the second most populous country in Africa after Nigeria, and its stability is supported by the West.
The U.S. military and intelligence services are working closely with Ethiopians to combat terrorist threats in the region, especially in Somalia, and virtually no country in Africa receives such support from the West.
Ethiopia’s economy is developing at an impressive rate.
Its infrastructure has improved significantly – there is even a new suburban train in the capital Addis Ababa.
And its streets are usually quiet, safe, and clean.
However, Ethiopia was hardly an example of democracy — human rights organizations are constantly mentioning government repressions — the opposition on the territory of the state was cut off because dissidents were actually silenced.
Many of them were sent to prison, killed, or exiled to remote deserts.
But it can change.
“If people are constantly oppressed and left no choice but to protest, the uprising will rise,” said Seyum Teshoma, a lecturer at the University of Central Ethiopia.
All young people are protesting.
The generation is protesting.
Complaints are numerous, starting with land use, ending with the seizure of power by the government coalition.
After the widely criticised elections last year, the government party and its allies have completely pushed the opposition out and now control 100 percent of parliament.
At the same time, tensions along the border with Eritrea are increasing; the struggle for this uncertain, controversial border killed hundreds of people in June.
Analysts fear that separatist groups, which have been more or less destroyed in recent years, such as the Oromo Liberation Front or the Ogaden National Liberation Front, may try to exploit unrest and re-arm themselves.
A number of factors explain why bitter feelings, boiling in the depths of the soul for several years, explode now.
The first, it seems, is completely harmless: smartphones.
In the last couple of years alone, a large number of Ethiopians have been able to communicate on social networks, as cheap smartphones have become commonplace, and internet service has become better.
Even when the government shuts down access to Facebook and Twitter, as it often happens, especially during protests, many people still find the opportunity to communicate through proxy servers that hide where they are.
Several young Ethiopians said that this is how they were organized for protests.
The second is that there is more solidarity between Oromo and Amhar, the two largest Ethiopian ethnic groups.
Oromo and Amhara are not natural allies.
Over the centuries, Amhar, from Ethiopia’s predominantly Christian highlands, flourished in politics and business, exploiting Oromo, many of which are Muslims and live in lowlands.
But it also changes.
"We will act together under a single start," said Mulatu Gemechu, the leader of Oromo.
The largest protests took place in the Amharic and Oromo districts.
Many of Amhari and Oromo feel that Ethiopia is unfairly dominated by members of the Tigray ethnic group, which accounts for about 6 per cent of the population and which controls military and intelligence services, trade and politics.
The third cause of unrest is the loss of Meles Zenaoui.
Meles, a former rebel leader, served as Prime Minister of Ethiopia for 17 years, until his death from an unknown illness in 2012.
He was considered a tactical genius, a man who could foresee danger.
Analysts claim that he was particularly skilled at identifying the first signals of discontent and using scouts to retrieve data and de-injure opponents.
"The current regime lacks common sense," said Abdi, an analyst for conflict situations.
The new Prime Minister of Ethiopia, Hailemariam Dessalen, appeared from nowhere and took the place of Meles.
Unlike Meles, who was native to the Tigray region of northern Ethiopia, Hailemariam is a southerner.
Analysts say he does not trust the security services controlled by Tigray.
Many fear that as a result, it will lead to even more bloodshed.
The last time Ethiopia experienced such unrest was in 2005, after thousands of people protested what analysts said appeared to have been elections that the government stalled and then falsified the results.
During the ensuing repressions, many Protestants were killed, albeit in smaller numbers than in recent months, and this period of unrest passed relatively quickly.
Development experts expressed their appreciation to Ethiopia’s leaders for the long-term development of infrastructure, such as a new intercity train and significant progress in combating poverty.
But it is clear that this has not stopped the growth of domestic dissatisfaction with the Ethiopian government.
And it takes on a dangerous ethnic form.
Last month, protesters in Gondar, the city of Amhar, attacked businesses belonging to Tigray, and anti-Tigray hatred on social media is becoming widespread.
Analysts say the protesters are putting the United States and other Western allies in an uncomfortable position.
The U.S. government has used Ethiopia as a base for unmanned flights over neighbouring Somalia, although it recently announced that it has closed the base.
On the one hand, it is clear that the West wants to support democracy, but on the other hand it does not want its ally to lose power in an already unstable region.
“And it will be difficult to get through this tight rope,” Abdi said.
