Adblock Plus, Facebook play "cat-mouse" about blocking ads
For companies that make money from online advertising, trying to bypass ad blocking software is a “cat-mouse” game, according to one of the companies that creates such software.
On Thursday, literally a few days after Facebook announced it was going to block ad blockers on its desktop site, Adblock Plus posted a blog entry that said users can update their filters in the program to block ads on social media.
On Tuesday, Facebook announced that the desktop version of the site is changing the ranks around its advertisements so that ad blockers find it harder to recognize which parts of the page are advertising.
But Adblock now claims it was able to bypass the new code.
In a blog post, Adblock spokesperson Ben Williams wrote that “this kind of mutual struggle between the community of open-source ad blockers and those who try to bypass it continues from the moment of the ad blocking invention,” and that it is possible that Facebook will present its own solution in the near future.
The fact that the world’s largest social network has entered the fight is a clear indication of how big a problem ad blockers have become for the industry.
Around 200 million people worldwide use ad blockers, according to last year’s Pagefair and Adobe surveys; nearly four times the number of people who used such software in 2013.
With 1.3 billion daily active users accessing Facebook via mobile devices, mobile advertising now accounts for 84 percent of Facebook’s advertising revenues.
However, the company is hunting for ad blockers on the desktop version, as mobile ad blockers are ineffective in Facebook’s mobile apps for the social network and Instagram, according to the representative.
But still, advertising in the desktop version is a profitable enough article for Facebook to consider such a step a profitable investment.
Also on Thursday, Facebook announced that it is going to update its “advertising preferences” tool to give people more control over how they are targeted.
On Thursday, Facebook said that the new Adblock filters are causing concern as they will also block some non-advertising content on the site.
“This will not be a positive experience for people, and we plan to solve this problem,” a Facebook spokesperson said in an official email.
Advertising blockers are a rough tool, so instead we’ve focused on creating tools like Ad Preferences to hand control over to people.
A woman was moved on a Swiss highway in an episode of apparent suicide.
The victim was lying on the highway in the middle of the night.
Police call on witnesses after several vehicles were moved on the highway early on Thursday morning in an apparent attempt to commit suicide.
The incident took place on the A1 near Morge in the canton of Wo just after midnight on Thursday.
The woman was lying on the road in the dark "in a gesture of despair" and was hit by several vehicles, police said in a statement.
Apparently, in an attempt to kill himself, the victim, a 49-year-old Swiss woman, hit several vehicles, including a truck.
She died on the spot.
Several of the drivers involved have already been questioned, but the identity of some has not yet been established, police said, calling on them and someone else, who witnessed the incident, to respond.
A criminal case was launched, a "logical" step in such a situation, said lawyer Gilles Hofstetter Le Tribune de Geneve.
However, it is yet to be determined whether any of the drivers involved will be charged.
Was it possible to avoid a hit?
That's what the prosecutor should determine," Hofstetter said.
Two other similar cases over the past five years suggest that drivers will not be held accountable.
In each case — both involving a man walking in the dark on the highway — a sentence has been issued that drivers cannot expect an accidental meeting with a pedestrian on the highway in the middle of the night, the newspaper reports.
Last year, the officer was acquitted of causing death by negligence after she hit and killed a man lying on the A1 near Payerne on the night of August 2014.
The 22-year-old victim drank and lost consciousness on the road, the court heard.
