NASA's climate model: Venus was once habitable
Venus may have once been habitable, according to NASA’s new climate model estimates.
Scientists from the Nassau Institute for the Study of Goddard Space have developed a model for studying the past of Venus, using tools and algorithms similar to those used by climatologists.
The model was designed to determine if there could ever be conditions on Venus, with its hot water-free surface and an atmosphere saturated with carbon dioxide, like Earth's.
Scientists have previously suggested that the small speed of rotation of Venus is due to its dense atmosphere.
But the latest modelling suggests that Venus probably could have had a diluted atmosphere like Earth's, and still rotate slowly.
The model also looked at the topography of early Venus.
There were probably more dry regions on the planet than on Earth, but once upon a time there was enough water and enough geographic variability to create living conditions and prevent rapid evaporation.
Early Venus also favored the sun, which was 30 percent fainter.
"According to the GISS model, the slow rotation of Venus puts its daily side of the sun for almost two months at a time," GISS scientist Anthony Del Henio said in a press release.
This heats the planet’s surface and produces rain, which creates a thick layer of clouds that acts as an umbrella that protects the planet’s surface from a significant portion of solar heat.
The result is the average climatic temperatures, which, surprisingly, are a few degrees colder than they are today on Earth.
The model shows the history of Venus, similar to the development previously assumed by experts in the study of planets.
Despite the fact that Venus may have once been inhabited, it has been exposed to too much heat and ultraviolet radiation for several billion years.
Its oceans evaporated and its water vapor was burned by ultraviolet radiation.
When its hydrogen leaked, only a dense atmosphere of carbon dioxide with a lethal greenhouse effect remained — that is, Venus, as we know it today.
The researchers shared the results of their new Venus climate model in the journal Geophysical Research Letters.
Patrick Roy resigns as Avalanche coach
Patrick Roy left the position of coach and vice president of hockey at Colorado Avalanche on Thursday, citing a lack of influence during the team’s decision-making process.
Executive Vice President/Chief Manager of the Colorado team Joe Sakik confirmed the news and noted that the club will start looking for a new coach immediately.
“Over the past three years, I have been serving as head coach and vice president of hockey at Colorado Avalanche with energy, passion and determination,” Roy, 50, said in a statement.
“During the summer, I’ve been thinking long and hard about how I could improve this team to give it the depth it needs and raise it to a higher level.
In order to achieve this goal, the vision of the coach and vice president of hockey activities must fit perfectly with the vision of the organization.
He must also have the right to vote when making decisions that affect the work of the team.
These conditions are not met at the moment.
Sakik, who hired Roy on May 23, 2013, thanked Roy for his contribution to the team.
"Patrick informed me of his decision today," Sakik said.
We appreciate everything he has done for our organization and wish him success in the future.
Roy won the Jack Adams Award as the league's best coach during his first season with the Avalanche team in 2013-2014.
He led the club to 112 points and a win in the Central Division, but Colorado was defeated by Minnesota in the first round of the playoffs and lost the playoffs in the last two years.
The Avalanche team announced a 39-39-4 rating in the 2015–16 season and five points behind the Wild team in the fight for the second qualifying round to participate in the Western Conference.
The Hall of Fame goalkeeper Roy won four Stanley Cups, two with the Montreal Canadiens and the Avalanche.
North Sea Oilmen Renew Negotiations and Suspend Strike
Working strikes on the salaries of oilmen in the North Sea have been suspended, and all sides of the discussion are beginning a new round of negotiations, the leading representatives of the parties said.
The strikes against the oil service company Wood Group were sporadically organized on platforms in the North Sea, run by Royal Dutch Shell.
“Wood Group and the Unite and RMT alliances can confirm that we have agreed to resume the negotiation process to resolve the ongoing disputes,” the statement said.
We will hold several full-time meetings over the next few weeks, starting at the beginning of next week, to look at the issues with a fresh look.
Trade unions said their recent action, which they said was the first in more than 25 years, was directed against potential wage cuts of up to 30 percent.
Wood Group this year cut rates paid to contractors working in the North Sea by about 9 percent due to negative market tensions, according to the report.
The company’s interest rates fell after a 10 percent reduction in rates for contracted employees working on the shores in 2014.
According to the company, additional cuts will give it the space it needs to overcome the decline of the market.
Shell, for its part, has cut thousands of people and announced plans to stop oil and gas operations in countries by up to 10 as it streamlines its operations as a result of its mega merger with the British energy company BG Group.
Energy companies are under pressure because of the declining prices of crude oil: the economic situation has deteriorated due to the decision to leave the European Union, adopted by the UK in June.
Scottish Member of Parliament Dave Anderson met with trade union leaders earlier this week to discuss one of the biggest labor conflicts that have arisen in the North Sea in our era.
The North Sea, he said, is vital to the regional economy.
“In the North Sea, and across the country, we need an economy that would work for the majority, not just for some,” he said in a statement.
Less than $1.4 billion in spending on new projects in the North Sea is expected in 2016, in contrast to an average value of about $7 billion over the past five years.
Kepler measures the speed of rotation of stars in the Pleiades accumulation
The last mission of the Kepler Space Telescope helped astronomers to assemble the most complete catalog of rotational speeds of stars in the Pleiades cluster.
The new data helps astronomers understand why the stars in the cluster rotate at different speeds, as well as how the periods of rotation relate to the formation of planets.
“We hope that by comparing our results with other stellar clusters, we will learn more about the relationship between the mass of the star, its age and even the history of its solar system,” said in a press release by Intiflisky, a researcher at the Intif Center.
The Pleiades accumulation is 445 light years from Earth.
Many of the stars in the cluster are now only reaching maturity; they were born about 125 million years ago.
They're spinning as fast as they'll never be again.
At their peak speeds of rotation, these adult stars emit large amounts of stellar wind.
Traveling through the magnetic fields of the stars, these winds act as a deterrent to the stars.
As the star ages, its rotational speed begins to slow down.
Kepler measures the speed of rotation of each star, tracking the time between the appearance of recognizable star spots — such as sunspots.
The newest catalog of rotational speeds suggests that more massive stars are rotating more slowly than less massive stars are rotating.
Fishall compares stars to dancers: larger ones make pirouettes slower than smaller ones.
