Since the Pleiades accumulation is so close, it serves as the ideal cosmic laboratory to compare the properties of stars with the speeds of rotation.
"The Pleiades star accumulation provides a starting point for theoretical models of the rotation of stars, both young and old," said Riball.
We want to know a lot more about how, where and why the stars slow their rotation speed and hang their "dancing shoes" on the nail, figuratively speaking.
Riball and her colleagues detailed their latest analysis of the speeds of rotation of the Pleiades in three new articles, which will soon be published in the Astronomical Journal.
