Clamping down between Angola and South Africa, Namibia suffered greatly during a long struggle against apartheid.
However, since independence from South Africa in 1990, this country, with a population of 2.4 million people, has achieved tremendous success, especially in the last few years.
The main reason for Namibia’s success is that the government pays great attention to education.
While people in developed countries perceive free primary and secondary education as self-evident, in many poor countries secondary and even primary schools demand tuition fees.
Moreover, governments are often advised to introduce a tuition fee for "cost reimbursement".
However, in Namibia, primary school education is free of charge.
In addition, secondary education has been free since 2015.
The country ' s authorities are also actively working in other important areas.
Efforts to eradicate malaria have reduced the number of annual cases of malaria by 97% over the past decade.
Contrary to the international trend of increasing inequality, it is decreasing in Namibia.
Compared to the 1993 indicator, the Gini ratio, the standard indicator of income inequality, fell by 15 points.
Then, 23 years ago, this figure was one of the highest in the world.
Poverty dropped from 69 per cent in 1993 to less than 30 per cent.
The number of people living in extreme poverty (less than $1.90 per day) also declined, from nearly 53 percent to less than 23 percent.
Namibia also has the highest ranking of free speech in Africa, according to Reporters Without Borders.
The country has far ahead of the United States and other wealthy states.
In addition, the country has a favorable rating – one of the highest in Africa – in the “Corruption Perception Index”, which is made up of human rights defenders from Transparency International.
Even now that commodity prices are falling, Namibia is able to maintain its high growth rate.
At the same time, the debt-to-GDP ratio is around 25%, which is less than 1/3 of the debt level in the United States and most European countries.
Of course, there are problems in Namibia.
Unemployment, at least according to traditional estimation methods, is still quite high – almost 28%.
And, like other countries in the region, Namibia ' s high level of HIV/AIDS - almost 17% of the population is infected.
According to World Bank estimates, Namibia is among the countries with above-average incomes, but the authorities insist that their state is actually a developing country.
Namibia, of course, is facing some of the difficulties inherent in the poorly developed economies.
The state has to develop a very large and dry country with a small population.
On the territory of the country in the deserts live isolated nomadic tribes of hunter-gatherer, which in some way must be integrated into modern society, without losing their identity.
Integrating people who were on the periphery of the world economy a quarter of a century ago is not an easy task for any country.
It is even more difficult for Namibia: like any other country in the world, it is facing the consequences of climate change.
However, Namibia did not think to let go, the country solves the problems it faces.
Almost immediately after independence, the authorities engaged in the creation of a diversified economy and a united society.
It is noteworthy that the competing political factions have come together to work for the common good.
Indeed, Namibia provides inexpensive medical care not only to its own citizens, but also to its neighbours.
About 15-20% of the visitors to medical institutions in the northern regions of Namibia are Angolan citizens.
No one in Namibia is talking about building a wall that would separate the country from its poor and corrupt neighbors.
The Namibians realized that the neighbors were not chosen, and therefore decided not to conflict with them, but to cooperate - to share scarce water resources, to participate in regional health projects, to encourage investment and exchange of students.
In addition, the Government of Namibia has rightly argued that rich natural resources can easily become a curse, contributing to the enrichment of the few at the expense of many.
The authorities understand that the proceeds from Namibia’s natural resources need to be invested in infrastructure and production capacity.
They are also aware that it would be irresponsible not to strive to make the most out of the country’s sales of resources, and are revising investment laws and mining contracts to make sure this is the case.
Transparency is crucial to this process, and therefore the strong support of the Government for freedom of expression is so important.
As the head of state Hague Gaingob noted, the media often say what he does not like.
But after fighting for freedom from apartheid in South Africa, Namibia must defend the freedoms it has received, the president said.
Not all of Namibia ' s key resources are depleted.
