Many have heard of the "Golden Varna" - the oldest gold objects created by man (4600 - 4200 BC).
Perhaps this was the loudest archaeological sensation of the 1970s: in Bulgaria, at the excavations of the Varna necropolis, a fantastic number of gold artifacts were found - more than three thousand total weight 6 kilograms.
Only one tomb, known as “Tomb No. 43”, was used to extract 990 gold objects weighing more than 1.5 kg.
However, the official status of the world’s oldest gold may soon shift to an imperceptible-looking bell discovered by archaeologists in July this year.
And again in Bulgaria - in a prehistoric settlement known as Tell the Young.
Unlike Varna, a port city, Tell Yunacite is located far from the sea, near the village Yunacite of the Pazardzhik district.
The busine is a golden strip, wrapped in a ring.
Yavor Boyajjiev, the head of the excavations at Tella Yunaci, dated the discovery 4600 BCE and stated that it was at least 200 years older than the gold of Varna.
The treasures of Varna, we recall, date from about the same period, 4600 - 4200 BC.
Technologies that allow metal to be dated with impeccable accuracy do not currently exist.
How can we be sure that gold is more ancient than gold?
Apparently, Professor Boyajjiev knows more than he told Reuters: "I am quite sure that the gold of the Youth is older than the gold of Varna."
It’s a discovery of extreme importance: it’s apparently a tiny object, but it’s big enough to take a fitting place in history.
In an interview with Reuters, Boyajjiev said that in the near future scientists will analyze the composition of the metal, as well as again and more carefully study the archaeological layer, where the gold artifact was found.
This will help to date the bus as accurately as possible.
The location also explains a lot.
Tell the Youth is a famous settlement, even if you’ve never heard of it.
Today, Tell the Young is considered to be the oldest “city” in Europe.
Tell was founded by descendants of people who migrated to Europe from Anatolia (modern Turkey) in the 7th millennium BC.
Over the following centuries, metal processing in this region developed rapidly, from the development of the first metallurgical skills to the creation of a full-fledged industry.
In the national historiography for this archaeological community there is a special name: Balkan-Carpathian metallurgical province.
In the 5th millennium BC around the centers of metalworking began to appear urban type settlements.
They are now called the oldest cities of Europe.
Of these, the Tell Youth is perhaps the oldest, as artifacts were found here in 4900 BC.
I would call Tell the Youngers a prototype of a modern city, although it is a very ancient settlement, even compared to Mesopotamia.
“This place is a thousand years older than Sumer,” Bojajiev says, referring to the common belief that urban culture originated in southern Mesopotamia – modern Iraq.
It was the first city in the usual sense of the word.
The excavations of Tella Youth have been carried out since 1976.
During this time, archaeologists have excavated almost 12 hectares, which is about a third of the estimated total area of the settlement.
The remains of the fortress wall, which once reached a height of three meters, were found.
There is little left of houses and workshops, but archaeologists clearly distinguish streets, public buildings, urban dense buildings, "business center" and residential outskirts.
Young people are often referred to as the “bird city”: dozens of clay figures of birds have been found here.
All the birds are depicted in a state of rest, hence the assumption that they were not decorative objects, but the object of the local cult.
The "bird city" was destroyed around 4100 BC - possibly by Indo-European tribes coming from the north-east.
Nomads did not have cities, but had horses and weapons.
The three-metre walls of the fortress did not stop them.
Archaeologists have discovered obvious signs of a brutal slaughter: inside the houses were found the remains of old men, women and children with traces of wounds inflicted by battle axes.
New discoveries and new facts appear every year, changing the habitual perceptions of the ancient history of mankind.
Bulgarian archaeologists are increasingly talking not about individual cultures, but about the “lost” first civilization of Europe born in the Balkans.
A powerful stimulus in the search for this civilization was the "Gold of Varna", found relatively recently, in 1972.
It is logical that the gold luxuries of Varna should have preceded something - something like a tiny gold beads created in Tell the Young.
